sys_variable_value.value:
/*
Here you can dynamically create a menu playlist by returning "answer" as a JSON object of the following format:

answer = {
  "1": {
      "say": "https://some_url.com/options/one.mp3",
      "myCustomData": "some data here"
  },
  "2": {
      "say": "https://some_url.com/options/two.mp3",
      "myCustomData": "some other data here"
  },
  "3": {
      "say": "type 3 to speak to a representative",
      "language": "en-US",
      "myCustomData": "some more data here"
  }
};

The "answer" JSON object's attributes must be number values that match what you expect the caller to type in.
Each attribute value is another JSON object which contains at least one mandatory "say" attribute.

The "say" attribute's value can either be a text-to-speech string, or a URL to a pre-recorded message.
If the "say" attribute is text-to-speech, you can add an optional "language" attribute which will contain the language code in the format xx-XX (e.g. fr-CA for Canadian French).

As shown in the example above, you can mix and match both types of "say" attributes.
In addition to the "say" attribute, you can optionally add your own data as extra attributes.

This activity will make your entire "answer" JSON object available in the workflow's scratchpad as workflow.scratchpad.menu.(activityName)
For instance if your activity name is "choices", you can retrieve the menu playlist using either workflow.scratchpad.menu.choices or workflow.scratchpad.menu["choices"] after the activity has successfully executed.
Your workflow can have several such menus since each one is named.

Example of how to retrieve menu information in a different activity (e.g. in a Say activity):

var previousActivity = "choices";
var choicesMenu = workflow.scratchpad.menu[previousActivity];
var menuItem = choicesMenu[workflow.scratchpad.digits];  // Selects the menu item based on the caller's digit input.
var selectedValue = menuItem.myCustomData;  // From the example above when digits is 3, the value of myCustomData is "some more data here"
var selectedLanguage = menuItem.language || "en-US";  // retrieves the menu item's language code, or "en-US" by default.

*/

